[1] California (Sacramento County)
Date: Tue 13 May 2014
Source: KCRA News [edited]
http://www.kcra.com/news/pertussis-outbreak-reported-in-sacramento-county/25934928


Health officials said Sacramento County is experiencing an outbreak of pertussis, which causes a loud, gasping whooping cough. Sacramento County officials reported 69 confirmed cases in 2014. In 2013, about 59 cases were reported for the entire calendar year. 11 of the 69 are young children and many are teenagers, the health department said.

Sacramento County public health officer Dr Olivia Kasirye said it's not uncommon for parents not to know what their child is suffering from when it comes to whooping cough. "If you have enough people immunized, you can stop it from spreading," Kasirye said. "It's spread through the air, through droplets -- usually, you have to be in pretty close contact with the person."

Schools and daycares are susceptible. What may appear to be a slight cough at first can get much worse. "If it's a child, sometimes they go blue in the face," Kasirye said. "They might even start throwing up and they might have the characteristic whoop at the end of an episode (of) coughing." Kasirye said it can be especially challenging to spot in babies who may only appear to have the sniffles.

[Byline: Gamaliel Ortiz]

