[2] California (Napa County)
Date: Fri 9 May 2014
Source: CBS San Francisco and Bay City News Service [edited]
http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2014/05/09/cases-disease-whooping-cough-pertussis-on-rise-napa-county/


Cases of pertussis, a potentially deadly disease also known as whooping cough, are on the rise in Napa County in 2014, Napa County's top health official said. Napa County Public Health Officer Dr Karen Smith said 17 cases have been reported so far in 2013, 9 of them in the last 2 weeks. There were 13 pertussis cases in Napa County in all of 2013. All but 3 of this year's [2014], 17 reported cases have been in children of middle or high school age, Smith said.

Smith urged women in their 3rd trimester of pregnancy to get vaccinated for pertussis to provide protection of the infant through transfer of antibodies from the mother before birth and by preventing the mother from passing a pertussis infection to the young infant after birth. Family members and childcare providers who have contact with the infant also should be vaccinated, health officials said.

Pertussis is cyclical and peaks every 3 to 5 years, health officials said. The last epidemic in California was in 2010 when there were 9100 cases statewide and 10 infant deaths.

All of Napa County's neighboring counties also are experiencing a high rate of pertussis, public health officials said.

